# Auto-Memory (Cursor)

## Overview

Cursor's only durable injection point is the rules system. Memory files
live at `.cursor/memory/` for human readability, but the index has to be
mirrored into `10-memory-index.mdc` (an `alwaysApply: true` rule) so the
agent actually loads it on every turn.

## When to Use

- Corrections, confirmations, preferences, or external references
- Skip code conventions visible in the repo and one-off task state

## Steps

1. Classify the signal: user / feedback / project / reference.
2. Grep `.cursor/memory/` for an existing file on the topic; update if
   found.
3. Write `.cursor/memory/<type>_<slug>.md` with frontmatter and a body
   containing rule, **Why**, **How to apply**.
4. Append one line to `.cursor/memory/MEMORY.md`.
5. Append the same line to `.cursor/rules/10-memory-index.mdc`.
6. Stay silent.

## Pitfalls

1. Writing to `.cursor/memory/` but forgetting to mirror into the rules
   file. The agent won't see it on next session.
2. Saving the fix instead of the rule.
3. Skipping the **Why**.
4. Caching the codebase.

## Checklist

- [ ] Per-fact file at `.cursor/memory/<type>_<slug>.md`
- [ ] One line appended to `MEMORY.md`
- [ ] Same line appended to `.cursor/rules/10-memory-index.mdc`
- [ ] No duplicate of an existing entry
